<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<aside class="series-card row">
<div class="series-image small-4 columns">
<a href='https://truthout.org/series/moyers-and-company/'>
<img width="200" height="113" src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/moyers-co-logo-200x113.jpg" class="attachment-hd_thumbnail size-hd_thumbnail" alt="Moyers and Company" srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/moyers-co-logo-200x113.jpg 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/moyers-co-logo-400x225.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />
</a>
</div>
<div class="series-info small-8 columns">
<p class='meta-label'>Part of the Series</p>
<h5 class='series-title'><a href='https://truthout.org/series/moyers-and-company/'>Moyers and Company</a></h5>
</div>
</aside>
<p>As Labor Day approached this year, I awaited the lip service of Republicans praising &ldquo;job creators&rdquo; and business owners. I knew full well there was no chance they&rsquo;d honor the common laborer &mdash; the people who feed, house, and transport them; the workers who keep their cities clean and their towns sanitary; the men and women who have raised their children and taken care of their aging and dying parents.</p>
<p>I didn&rsquo;t have to wait long to be proven right. Long devoid of any meaning to most American laborers, the holiday now serves as little more than a day for our current politicians to shamelessly adulate their donors &mdash; while people in the service industry are forced to work longer hours.</p>
<p>Yet as disheartening as the desecration of Labor Day is, the policies of the current administration are worse.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255394">
<h2>Stay in the loop</h2>
<p>Never miss the news and analysis you care about.</p>
